<h2>Hard-Coded Test Page</h2>
<p>This page is a <strong>static example</strong> created specifically for testing and demonstration purposes within the CMS environment.</p>

<h3>What Does &quot;Hard-Coded&quot; Mean Here?</h3>
<p>
    The content you see on this page including the title, headings, paragraphs, and any images, is <strong>not stored in the CMS database</strong>.
</p>
<p>It is written directly into the PHP file for this template <code>test.phtml</code> using standard HTML and PHP.</p>

<ul>
    <li><strong>No Database Queries:</strong> Viewing this page does not execute any complex database queries typically used to retrieve page content, metadata, or widgets.</li>
    <li><strong>No CMS Editing:</strong> You <strong>cannot</strong> edit this content through the administrative backend of the CMS. Any changes must be made directly to the source PHP file.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Purpose of This Page</h3>
<ol>
    <li><strong>Demonstrate Hard-Coding Capability:</strong> Show a clear example of how to manually bypass the CMS&#39;s dynamic content generation to insert static HTML/text directly into a page template file. This confirms the page rendering pipeline (PHP execution and HTML output) is working.</li>
    <li><strong>Provide a Baseline:</strong> Offer a known, stable example against which the functionality of <strong>dynamic content pages</strong> can be compared.</li>
    <li><strong>Illustrate the Exception (Not the Rule):</strong> While this method is <strong>possible</strong> for certain highly specialized or legacy pages that never change, it is <strong>not encouraged</strong> for standard content. The core benefit of a CMS is centralizing content management, and hard-coding defeats this purpose. <strong>Best practice</strong> is to manage all content through the administrative interface and database.</li>
</ol>

